\(\therefore \quad \mathrm { M } \propto R\)

If radius becomes double then mass will becomes twice.

quest_title: In a circuit, the value of the alternating current is measured by hot wire ammeter as 10 amperes. Its peak value will be
explanation_txt:
When current is passed through a hot wire ammeter, power is dissipated in the form of heat on the wire due to its resistance and the ammeter points the value of current based on the thermal expansion.

As the power emitted due to AC signal depends upon rms value of current, the ammeter measures \(I_{rms}\). Hence, peak value of current \(= I _ { r m s } \times \sqrt { 2 } = 14.14 \) Amperes

quest_title: A person is standing on 'a' railway, when a train is approaching him, the frequency of whistle heard by him is 220Hz, but when train has crossed him, the frequency heard by him is 184Hz. The actual frequency of the whistle is
explanation_txt:
\({f}_{1}=\left(\cfrac{{v}}{{v}-{v}_{{s}}}\right) \times {f} \Rightarrow \cfrac{f}{f_{1}}=\left(\cfrac{{v}-{v}_{{s}}}{{v}}\right)\)
\(\Rightarrow \cfrac{f}{220}=1-\cfrac{{v}_{{s}}}{{v}} \cdots ({i}) \)
Again, \(f_{2}=\left(\cfrac{v}{v+v_{s}}\right) \times f \Rightarrow \cfrac{f}{f_{2}}=\left(\cfrac{v+v_{s}}{v}\right)\)
\(\Rightarrow \cfrac{f}{184}=1+\cfrac{v_{s}}{v} \cdots (ii) \)
Adding (i) and (ii) we get
\(\cfrac{f}{220}+\cfrac{f}{184}=2\)
\(\quad {f}=\cfrac{2 \times 220 \times 184}{220+184}=200.39=200 {Hz}\)
